ses and provide contextually relevant feedback.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on general automated assessment scoring methods that may not be well-suited for the specific needs of science education. The integration of human-in-the-loop chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with GPT-4 represents a novel approach that addresses these limitations.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing a human-in-the-loop system using GPT-4 for chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning. The system will be trained on a dataset of middle school science assessments, and its performance will be evaluated using metrics such as accuracy, relevance of feedback, and teacher satisfaction. Expected outcomes include a robust automated grading and feedback system that enhances student learning and reduces teacher workload.\n\nThis summary captures the essence of the conversation, highlighting the collaborative effort to develop a research proposal that addresses the identified gaps in automated grading and feedback generation for middle school science assessments."}
