esting and important?**\n   - Solving this problem can significantly reduce the burden on teachers while providing more accurate and personalized feedback to students, thereby enhancing their learning experience and development of STEM skills.\n\n3. **Why is it hard?**\n   - Challenges include ensuring the reliability of non-expert crowdworker judgments, designing effective comparative judgment methods, and integrating these with LLMs in a way that maintains accuracy and efficiency.\n\n4. **Why hasn't it been solved before?**\n   - Previous research has focused on individual components (LLM grading, crowdworker judgments) but has not combined them effectively. There is a gap in understanding how to integrate these methods to improve overall system performance.\n\n5. **What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n   - **Methodology:** Develop a framework that integrates non-expert crowdworkers and comparative judgment with LLMs. Use a dataset of student responses in STEM formative assessments.\n   - **Metrics:** Evaluate the system using metrics such as inter-rater reliability, feedback quality, and teacher satisfaction.\n   - **Expected Outcomes:** Improved reliability and quality of feedback, reduced grading time for teachers, and enhanced student learning outcomes.\n\n### Conclusion\nThe conversation focused on enhancing an LLM-based grading system by integrating non-expert crowdworkers and comparative judgment to improve inter-rater reliability and feedback quality in STEM education. The proposed research idea aims to address this gap and provide practical solutions for formative assessments in K-12 STEM contexts."} {"type": "action_function_call", "action_name": "new_communication_session", "args": {"target_agent_id": "agent1", "message": "Let's discuss the potential of integrating non-expert crowdworkers and comparative judgment with our LLM-based grading system to further improve inter-rater reliability and feedback quality."}, "result": {"succes