nd provide consistent, high-quality feedback is a significant challenge.\n\n5. **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n   - **Methodology:** Develop a framework that integrates non-expert crowdworkers and comparative judgment with LLMs. Use a dataset of student responses in STEM formative assessments to train and validate the system.\n   - **Metrics:** Evaluate the system using metrics such as inter-rater reliability, feedback quality, and teacher satisfaction. Use statistical methods to compare the performance of the integrated system with existing LLM-based grading systems.\n   - **Expected Outcomes:** Improved reliability and quality of feedback, reduced grading time for teachers, and enhanced student learning outcomes. The system should provide more accurate and personalized feedback, leading to better student performance and engagement in STEM education.\n\n### Final '5q' Proposal:\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"new_communication_session\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"target_agent_id\": \"agent1\",\n    \"message\": \"### '5q' Research Proposal\\n\\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\\n- How can we improve the inter-rater reliability and feedback quality of an LLM-based grading system for formative assessments in STEM education?\\n\\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\\n- Solving this problem can significantly reduce the burden on teachers while providing more accurate and personalized feedback to students, thereby enhancing their learning experience and development of STEM skills.\\n\\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\\n- Challenges include ensuring the reliability of non-expert crowdworker judgments, designing effective comparative judgment methods, and integrating these with LLMs in a way that maintains accuracy and efficiency.\\n\\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\\n- Previous research has focused on individual components (LLM grading, crowdworker judgments) but has not combined 