nses and integrating LLMs and GNNs effectively.\\n- **Question 4:** Previous research lacks integrated solutions addressing full formative assessment needs in STEM education and specific applications of GNNs.\\n- **Question 5:** The approach involves a human-in-the-loop system using LLMs for scoring and feedback, with GNNs for deeper insights into student learning processes. Evaluation will use a middle school Earth Science curriculum dataset, focusing on accuracy, reliability, and impact on student learning outcomes.\\n\\n**Outcome:**\\n- The next steps involve seeking feedback, refining methodology, addressing technical and ethical challenges, conducting pilot testing, and documenting the research process for publication.\\n\\nThis summary captures the key points, themes, and decisions made in the conversation, providing a clear path forward for the research proposal."}'}, {'agent6': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session 1dcf3d61-9ffa-479e-b02e-040bc7216d9f", "full_chat_history": "In Session 1dcf3d61-9ffa-479e-b02e-040bc7216d9f \\nFrom agent6 to agent1: Finalized \'5q\' Research Proposal for Automated Grading and Feedback Generation in K-12 Mathematics Assessments\\n\\nDear Research Team,\\n\\nI hope this message finds you well. As part of our ongoing collaboration, I have finalized the \'5q\' research proposal for our project on developing an automated grading and feedback generation system for K-12 mathematics assessments using chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, specifically leveraging the AMMORE dataset.\\n\\nPlease find the finalized \'5q\' proposal below:\\n\\n### Final \'5q\' Research Proposal\\n\\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\\nWhat is the need for an automated grading and feedback generation system for K-12 mathematics assessments that leverages chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, specifically using the AMMORE dataset?\\n\\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\\nAddressing this problem is crucial for reducing the time-consuming and error-prone nature of grading formative assessments in K-12 mathematics education. Such a system can provide timely and personalized feedback to students, enhancing their learning experience and supporting teachers in identifying and addressing students\' difficulties more effectively. This research can also contribute to the broader adoption of open-ended questions in formative assessments, promoting deeper student engagement and understanding.\\n\\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\\nDeveloping an automated system that can accurately grade and provide meaningful feedback in mathematics domains, where understanding and reasoning are key, is challenging. Naive approaches may fail due to the variability in student responses and the need for nuanced understanding of mathematical concepts. Technical, theoretical, and practical obstacles include ensuring the system\'s ability to handle unstructured responses and provide contextually relevant feedback.\\n\\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?**\\nPrevious research has focused on general automated assessment scoring methods that may not be well-suited for the specific needs of mathematics education. The integration of chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, specifically using the AMMORE dataset, represents a novel approach that addresses these limitations. This approach leverages the strengths of LLMs in handling complex and nuanced student responses, providing a more accurate and contextually relevant grading system.\\n\\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\\nThe proposed methodology involves developing a system using chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, specifically using the AMMORE dataset. The system will be trained on a dataset of K-12 mathematics assessments, and its performance will be evaluated using metrics such as accuracy, relevance of feedback, and teacher satisfaction. Expected outcomes include a robust automated grading and feedback system that enhances student learning and reduces teacher workload, as well as a deeper understanding of the capabilities and limitations of LLMs in educational assessment.\\n\\nPlease review the proposal and provide your feedback. Your insights will be invaluable as we move forward with this research.\\n\\nBest regards,\\n\\n[Your Name]\\n\\nOnce the proposal is shared, I will schedule a meeting to discuss any feedback and make any necessary adjustments before proceeding with the research.\\n", "session_id": "### Summary of the Chat History\\n\\n**Context and Participants:**\\n- **Agent6** has finalized a \'5q\' research proposal for an automated grading and feedback generation system for K-12 mathematics assessments.\\n- The proposal is intended to be shared with the research team for feedback and discussion.\\n\\n**Key Themes:**\\n1. **Problem Statement:** The need for an automated grading system that uses chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, specifically the AMMORE dataset.\\n2. **Importance:** Reducing the time-consuming and error-prone nature of grading formative assessments, providing timely and personalized feedback, and promoting deeper student engagement.\\n3. **Challenges:** Developing a system that can accurately grade and provide meaningful feedback in mathematics, addressing variability in student responses, and ensuring contextually relevant feedback.\\n4. **Novelty:** Leveraging chain-of-thought reasoning and in-context learning with LLMs, which is a novel approach compared to previous research.\\n5. **Methodology and Expected Outcomes:** The system will be trained on K-12 mathematics assessments and evaluated using metrics like accuracy, relevance of feedback, and teacher satisfaction. The goal is to enhance student learning and reduce teacher workload.\\n\\n**Next Task:**\\n- **Action:** Share the finalized \'5q\' research proposal with the research team.\\n- **Communication:** Send an email or share the document through a collaborative platform used by the research team.\\n- **Follow-Up:** Schedule a meeting to discuss feedback and make necessary adjustments.\\n\\n**Example Communication:**\\n- **Subject:** Finalized \'5q\' Research Proposal for Automated Grading and Feedback Generation in K-12 Mathematics Assessments\\n- **Message:** The email includes the finalized proposal and requests feedback from the team.\\n\\n**Outcomes:**\\n- The research team will review the proposal and provide insights.\\n- A meeting will be scheduled to discuss feedback and make any necessary adjustments before proceeding with the research.\\n\\nThis summary captures the essential points of the conversation, highlighting the purpose, content, and next steps for the research proposal."}'}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "What is the need for an automated grading and feedback generation system for K-12 Earth Science formative assessments that leverages Large Language Models (LLMs) with in-context learning and chain-of-thought reasoning to provide accurate and context-aware feedback?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for reducing the time-consuming and error-prone process of grading formative assessments in K-12 science education. It will enable teachers to focus more on student learning and less on administrative tasks. This research will advance the field of educational technology by demonstrating the potential of LLMs in providing nuanced feedback, which can significantly enhance student learning outcomes. The broader implications include the development of more effective and scalable educational tools that can be adapted to various STEM subjects.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenge lies in developing LLMs that can accurately interpret and provide feedback on open-ended, unstructured student responses in science domains. Naive approaches may fail due to the variability in student vocabulary, stylistic expression, and the need for contextual understanding. Technical obstacles include ensuring the LLMs can handle the nuances of scientific reasoning and provide actionable feedback. Theoretical challenges involve aligning the automated feedback with specific learning goals and understanding the cognitive processes involved in scientific problem-solving.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on automated grading for well-structured responses and has not fully addressed the complexities of open-ended, context-dependent questions in science education. Existing solutions often lack the nuance required for science domains and may not provide actionable feedback. The gap in research is the integration of in-context learning and chain-of-thought reasoning to improve the accuracy and relevance of automated feedback. Our approach differs by specifically targeting Earth Science and employing advanced LLM techniques to address these challenges.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed methodology includes iterative prompt engineering, chain-of-thought reasoning, alignment with learning goals, and the use of transfer learning. We will utilize a dataset of middle school Earth Science formative assessments and employ metrics such as accuracy, relevance, and student satisfaction to evaluate the system. The expected outcomes include a robust automated grading and feedback system that can significantly reduce teacher workload and improve student learning outcomes in Earth Science."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': ["In Session 4e1be717-f8c9-4e1b-903e-d892450774a6 \nFrom agent5 to agent6: Here is the refined research proposal in the '5q' format. Could you please provide your feedback on i